04821nam a22006375i 9780271030371DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212006pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710303717 a10.1515/97802710303712doi  a(DE-B1597)584083  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aDK561b.J647 2006eb 7aHIS0320002bisacsh04a947/.2100720472221 aJohnson, Emily D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHow St. Petersburg Learned to Study Itself :bThe Russian Idea of Kraevedenie /cEmily D. Johnson. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b7 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tA Note on Transliteration and Translations -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction. Ways of Knowing: Russian Local Studies as an Identity Discipline -- t1 The Eighteenth- and Nineteenth-Century Tradition -- t2 The Art Journals of the Silver Age, St. Petersburg Preservationism, and the Guidebook -- t3 Old Petersburg After the Revolution -- t4 The Excursion Movement and Excursion Methodology -- t5 Excursion Primers and Literary Tours -- t6 Kraevedenie in St. Petersburg -- t7 Literary Kraevedenie -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the bookshops of present-day St. Petersburg, guidebooks abound. Both modern descriptions of Russia's old imperial capital and lavish new editions of pre-Revolutionary texts sell well, primarily attracting an audience of local residents. Why do Russians read one- and two-hundred-year-old guidebooks to a city they already know well? In How St. Petersburg Learned to Study Itself, Emily Johnson traces the Russian fascination with local guides to the idea of kraevedenie.Kraevedenie (local studies) is a disciplinary tradition that in Russia dates back to the early twentieth century. Practitioners of kraevedenie investigate local areas, study the ways human society and the environment affect each other, and decipher the semiotics of space. They deconstruct urban myths, analyze the conventions governing the depiction of specific regions and towns in works of art and literature, and dissect both outsider and insider perceptions of local population groups. Practitioners of kraevedenie helped develop and popularize the Russian guidebook as a literary form.Johnson traces the history of kraevedenie, showing how St. Petersburg-based scholars and institutions have played a central role in the evolution of the discipline. Distinguished from obvious Western equivalents such as cultural geography and the German Heimatkunde by both its dramatic history and unique social significance, kraevedenie has, for close to a hundred years, served as a key forum for expressing concepts of regional and national identity within Russian culture.How St. Petersburg Learned to Study Itself is published in collaboration with the Harriman Institute at Columbia University as part of its Studies of the Harriman Institute series.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aLocal historyxStudy and teachingzRussia (Federation)zSaint Petersburg. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271030371zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271030371423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271030371.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  